{
  "texts": [
    "Indeed, if as some researchers on 'event coding' in the neuroscience of intentional action have suggested, the representations underlying intentions always involves some reference to the ends that a prospective action is a means to, then it is reasonable to expect that agent's primary reasons never support intentions just to perform a basic action (see, e.g., Hommel et al., 2001).",
    "11 As Davidson notes (see Davidson, 2001a, ch. 1), representations on the agent 's part do not by themselves specify the particular action she does.",
    "The action is determined by the intention via its causal role.",
    "While this means that while intentions must represent a prospective action under a description that makes it intelligible as the fulfilment of an intention she has, this description can be radically uninformative about the action that is underway: Such descriptions are, to be sure, apt to be trivial and unrevealing; this is what ensures their existence.",
    "So, if I tie my shoelaces, here is a description of my movements: I move my body in just the way required to tie my shoelaces."
  ]
}